 Reson and Sensuallyte and Temple of Glas, the anonymous Court of Sapience and Assembly of Gods, James I's Kingis Quair, Charles d'Orleans' Fortunes Stabilnes, and William Dunbar's Golden Targe. This book offers the first full-length examination of these depictions, bringing out the receptionof classical culture. Via close readings of the various poets, it enables us to understand how her figure was used, and also, and most importantly, to interpret and transform the poetic and cultural traditions from which she springs. WILLIAM F. HODAPP is Professor of English and Coordinator of Medieval and Renaissance Studies at The College of St. Scholastica, Duluth, Minnesota.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAllegorical.  aArt.  aClassical Reception.  aCultural Insight.  aDream-Vision Poems.  aImages.  aLiterary Tradition.  aLiterature.  aMiddle Ages.  aMinerva.  aMythology.  aRepresentation.  aRoman Goddess.  aTransformation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446120?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446120423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446120/original  a978-3-11-143102-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles